    <h1 class="ui header" style="background-color: #ED5738">
      Why is it so hot?
    </h1>
  </div>

  <div class="ui text container">

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui red header">
        It's hot, and getting hotter.
      </h2>
      <p>
        Summers are normally hot, but average summer temperatures have been rising steadily over the last several years&mdash;and that's not normal.
      </p>

      <p>
       From 1981 to 2010, the average summer temperature in the Boston area was 69&deg;F. Since 2010, average summer temperatures have risen: by 2030, the average summer temperature could rise to 73&deg;F, and by 2050, 76&deg;F.
      </p>

      <img src="content/average-summer-temp-increase.png" />
      <p>
        <a href="https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/greenovateboston/pages/1182/attachments/original/1464977705/ClimateProjectionConsensusSummary_June2016.pdf?1464977705" target="_blank">
          Source: Climate Ready Boston, May 2016
        </a>
      </p>

    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui red header">
        It's been years since summer temperatures were normal.
      </h2>
      <p>
        Between 1971 and 2000, we experienced 11 days per year over 90&deg;F. By 2030, there may be 40 days above 90&deg;F, and by 2070 up to 90 days over 90&deg;F&mdash;nearly the entire summer. Summer could feel like one giant heat wave.
      </p>

      <img src="content/number-hot-days-increase.png" />
      <p>
        <a href="https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/greenovateboston/pages/1182/attachments/original/1464977705/ClimateProjectionConsensusSummary_June2016.pdf?1464977705" target="_blank">
          Source: Climate Ready Boston, May 2016
        </a>
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sotc/global/201606" target="_blank">
          According to NOAA
        </a>, "June 2016 marks the 34th consecutive June with global temperatures at least nominally above average. The last time global land surface temperatures were below average in June was in 1982."
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui red header">
        Why is this happening?
      </h2>
      <p>
        Hot days will increase in frequency and intensity over the next few decades as a result of human-driven climate change.
      </p>

      <p>
        Climate change may have a noticeable impact on us even by 2030, which is only 14 years away. To put things into perspective, 14 years in the past was the year 2002&mdash;not that far at all.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui red header">
        How will it feel?
      </h2>
      <p>
        In 2050, Massachusetts might feel like Maryland or Virginia, depending how well we curb greenhouse gas emissions. (See below map.) This might sound great at first&mdash;there may be more days you can visit the beach or use your swimming pool. However, heat waves are a leading cause of weather-related mortality in the United States, so higher temperatures may come with harsh consequences.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <img src="content/ma-map.png" />
      <p>
        <a href="http://www.ucsusa.org/sites/default/files/legacy/assets/documents/global_warming/pdf/confronting-climate-change-in-the-u-s-northeast.pdf" target="_blank">
          Source: Confronting Climate Change in the U.S. Northeast: Science, Impacts, and Solutions, NECIA, 2007.
        </a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui red header">
        What about the Snowpocalypse?
      </h2>
      <p>
        It may sound counterintuitive, but climate change can cause extreme weather events in both summer and winter&mdash;including the record 109" of snow that fell during the winter of 2014-15.
      </p>

      <p>
        In the summer, higher average temperatures mean hotter days. In the winter, warmer air evaporates more water. Storm systems use this extra water to produce snow. Climate change is causing higher temperatures in summer and record snowfall in winter.
      </p>

      <img src="content/rainfall-increase.png" />
      <p>
        <a href="https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/greenovateboston/pages/1182/attachments/original/1464977705/ClimateProjectionConsensusSummary_June2016.pdf?1464977705" target="_blank">
          Source: Climate Ready Boston, May 2016
        </a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui red header">
        What else might happen?
      </h2>
      <p>
        According to the Boston Research Advisory Group, increasing global temperatures are also raising sea level higher. This will likely cause more flooding and higher storm surges, which may damage coastal property and make insurance companies more reluctant to insure these types of places.
      </p>

      <p>
        Higher storm surges may erode or otherwise damage beaches, nature preserves, and other tourist destinations which boost our economy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui teal header">
        What can I do?
      </h2>
      <p>
        Climate change is hard problem to solve&mdash;there's no denying that&mdash;but we're hopeful that by taking action together, we can all participate to prevent the worst effects. Our choices about transportation, energy, and land use determine how climate change will impact us.
      </p>

      <p>
        We live in a society where it's easy to have a high carbon footprint by default. We encourage you to join us in taking action to help stabilize the climate by reducing your greenhouse gas emissions.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <h2 class="ui teal header">
        At home.
      </h2>
      <p>
        One of the most cost-effective steps you can take is to
        <a href="http://www.masssave.com/" target="_blank">
          get a home energy audit.
        </a>
        You can do an
        <a href="http://www.masssave.com/en/residential/home-energy-assessments/about-home-energy-assessments/online-home-energy-assessment" target="_blank">
          audit for free online
        </a>
        , or in-person with a contractor. This will reveal any leaks and gaps in insulation and window seals, which are usually easy and inexpensive to address, and which can make heating and cooling bills much less expensive.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="http://www.masssave.com/" target="_blank">
          Do an energy audit online or schedule one in person through MassSave.
        </a>
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="https://www3.epa.gov/climatechange/wycd/home.html" target="_blank">
